'''Alexis 'Lexi' Brasseur''' (26 December 1860 – 3 November 1924) was a [[Luxembourg]]eois playwright, composer, and metallurgist.

Born in [[Luxembourg City]] as the oldest son of [[Dominique Brasseur]], Brasseur attended the [[Athénée de Luxembourg]].  He followed this by studying law at the [[University of Bonn]], where he met [[Batty Weber]].<ref name="Mersch 95">Mersch (1959), p. 95</ref>  Brasseur received his doctorate in Luxembourg in 1886, and was [[call to the bar|called to the bar]], but showed little interest in working in the law.  He turned to [[metallurgy]], like his father and uncle [[Pierre Brasseur (Luxembourg)|Pierre]].<ref name="Mersch 95" />

In 1894, he had written a [[Comedy (drama)|comedy]] with Batty Weber called ''De Monoonk Phëlpp''.<ref>Mersch (1959), p. 96</ref>  In 1907, he moved to Paris, staying there for four years.<ref>Mersch (1959), pp. 95–6</ref>  Brasseur died in Luxembourg City on 3 November 1924.<ref name="Mersch 99">Mersch (1959), p. 99</ref>

Alexis Brasseur was a member of the prominent [[Brasseur family]].  His father, [[Dominique Brasseur|Dominique]], was a [[deputy (legislator)|deputy]] (1866 – 99) and [[mayor of Luxembourg City]] (1891 – 94).  His brother, [[Robert Brasseur|Robert]], was a deputy and founded the [[Liberal League (Luxembourg)|Liberal League]].<ref>Mersch (1959), p. 108</ref>  Alexis Brasseur married Jeanne Bian (1869–1960), sister of the liberal deputy [[Félix Bian]] and industrialist [[Émile Bian]].<ref name="Mersch 99" />  They had three children.<ref>Mersch (1959), p. 100</ref>

