{{Expand German|Anton Freissler|date=February 2011}} {{Infobox engineer |image = Anton Freissler.jpg |image_size = 150 |caption = |name = Anton Freissler |nationality = Austrian |birth_date = {{Birth date|1838|3|13}} |birth_place = [[Kujavy]], [[Moravia]], [[Austrian Empire]] |death_date = {{death date and age|1916|2|29|1838|3|13}} |death_place = Vienna |education = |spouse = |parents = |children = |discipline = |institutions = |practice_name = |significant_projects = [[elevator]]s |significant_design = |significant_advance = |significant_awards = }} '''Anton Freissler''', aka '''Anton Freißler''' (March 13, 1838 in Klantendorf ({{lang-cs|Kujavy}}, [[Moravian–Silesian Region]]) – February 29, 1916) invented and developed a number of paternoster and elevators.
== Biography == [[Image:Anton Freissler P.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Oldest Paternoster in Austria by Freissler, installed in 1911]] Freissler was born in [[Kujavy]] in northern Moravia, which was a part of Austrian empire. Freissler developed [[paternoster]]s and [[elevator]]s, which were sold very successfully throughout the empire and abroad. One of the oldest paternosters, installed in 1911, is still in use in the House of Industry in Vienna.
Freissler was also issued an [[imperial warrant]] as a Purveyor to the Imperial and Royal Court.
The company existed until the 1970s until it was incorporated into [[Otis Elevator Company|Otis]] Austria.
